stylometry: @risk helps you set up problems that are able to run simulations for business models.  The at risk helps you put probability variables into a problem and it runs the problem and runs through 1000 different iterations (answers when you are targeting a certain goal) .  After the simulation runs the function gives you a graph and different numbers such as the minimum maximum and mean and the standard deviation.  Your duty is to analyze these numbers and decide what level of risk you are going to take based on the different numbers yo uwere given for your problem.  For example in our projecet problem with the bakery we could have used risk to run a simulation for the price of marketing we performed and the expected profit.  It would have run a simulation and we would have been able to see if we spent a certain amount of marketing what the profit would be.  If we have 5 inputs it runs 1,000 iterations for each input and then gives you answers in the graph and number form after.
